{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:11.621Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Identifying Login Entrypoints**\n\nI've pinpointed three key entry points: `app/admin/login/page.tsx`, `app/login/page.tsx`, and `app/portal/login/page.tsx`. All of these render the `<SecureLogin>` component, opening up a direct path. If I build the ultimate login UI in `components/portal/SecureLogin.tsx`, I achieve a unified and premium login experience across the board.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:12.749Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing SecureLogin UI**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the design phase for `SecureLogin.tsx`. I've outlined the core UI elements based on requirements: GFF AI branding, email/password fields with placeholders, SSO placeholders, OTP login placeholders, a local development role preview, and a frontend-only notice. My focus is on creating a secure, enterprise-level feel while ensuring mobile excellence, accessibility, keyboard-friendliness, and a visually premium experience with subtle motion. I'm also planning the \"forgot password\" and \"contact support\" placeholders. I'll make the local session, and client roles to /portal/dashboard and GFF/admin roles to /admin/dashboard.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:14.590Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Structuring Login Component**\n\nI'm now focused on refining the structure and aesthetic of the `SecureLogin.tsx` component. I'm exploring layout options, aiming for a stunning grid or split layout. I've chosen a dark background and plan to incorporate subtle premium grids and glows, creating an executive aesthetic. I've also identified appropriate imports like `lucide-react` icons and a layout with a custom logo and interactive tabs. The tabs are the standard Auth with email and password, and OTP.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:16.433Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing Login Input Fields**\n\nI'm now implementing the actual login input fields. I'm focusing on making accessible and keyboard-interactive email and password fields with clear placeholders, utilizing `<input>` elements. I'll include a toggle for the password visibility. I'll also add placeholders for \"Forgot Password\" and a \"Initialize Secure Session\" button. Under the OTP tab, I'll design fields for email and a 6-digit OTP code, along with a \"Verify Passcode\" button. I'm also preparing placeholders for beautiful, clean SSO buttons and a contact support link.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:18.072Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Adding Role Switcher**\n\nI've decided to incorporate a \"Development Identity Switcher\" or \"Local Role Sandbox.\" I'm planning a prominent \"FRONTEND-ONLY NOTICE\" badge to emphasize client-side isolation. I'm building a scrollable list featuring the seven roles, each with an icon, title, description, clearance level, and color-coded theme. Upon role selection, the email field will be pre-filled with a mock email, and a mock password will also be automatically prepopulated. Finally, a new \"Authenticate Sovereign Enclave\" will drive the authentication UI.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:19.623Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Verifying Role Routing**\n\nI've just validated the role-based routing logic.  Submitting now creates a local preview session, directing client roles like 'client_admin' and 'client_member' to `/portal/dashboard`, while GFF and admin roles go to `/admin/dashboard`. The code `selectedRole.startsWith(\"client_\") ? \"/portal/dashboard\" : \"/admin/dashboard\"` works flawlessly.\n\nI'm now designing the custom SVG for GFF AI branding, thinking of a golden-ratio cube or a shield with nested hexagons to symbolize Garage, Foundry, and Factory. I'll make it premium and minimal, with a palette of `#009DFF` and deep silver.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:22.168Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing GFF AI Logo**\n\nI've just finished the GFF AI SVG logo, a set of nested hexagons representing the core structure of the Garage, Foundry, and Factory. It has a beautiful premium feel, perfect for a secure login experience. Now, I'm shifting focus to the OTP login panel. I'm planning to implement a tab system for \"Secure Keycard\" (Email/Password) and \"Single-Use Token\" (OTP). Additionally, I'll include SSO buttons, a \"Forgot Password\" feature, and a support contact.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:24.013Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining UI Interactivity**\n\nI'm now integrating micro-interactions. I'm focusing on mobile excellence with a responsive layout. The design employs `grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-8 w-full max-w-6xl` using Tailwind for a seamless experience. On mobile, the login form takes precedence, and the sandbox switcher/notice is styled in a compact format. I've designed an elegant, expensive-feeling background grid with a radial gradient for a modern aesthetic.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:26.264Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing Login Actions**\n\nI'm now implementing the click events and visual feedback for the local role sandbox. Hovering triggers a subtle glow effect with the card's theme color. Clicking plays a sound and updates the form, pre-filling email and secure token fields. Password visibility toggles now work. On submission, I'll validate form fields for both standard and OTP logins, displaying accessible error states if needed. If valid, I'll launch a visual scanning sequence with progress updates before redirecting. I will use the local session for local preview and routing!\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:27.800Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Constructing SecureLogin Code**\n\nI'm now diving into the complete implementation of `SecureLogin.tsx`, focusing on robust state management for the email, password, and OTP fields. I'm initializing the email field with the selected role's mock email and a placeholder password. The ultimate goal is creating an intuitive user interface, so form inputs are handled correctly.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:30.053Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Crafting Complete SecureLogin Component**\n\nI'm now building the final `SecureLogin.tsx` component, integrating credentials and OTP authentication methods, along with password reset and support modals. I'm focusing on responsiveness, dark mode, and accessibility using Tailwind CSS and ensuring a premium user experience with glassmorphic cards, sleek typography, and robust state management. I am meticulously reviewing the CSS classes and ensuring that all features are in place before I proceed with any lint tests. I want to build a truly amazing experience here!\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T02:23:31.655Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Importing Lucide Icons**\n\nI've imported a comprehensive set of Lucide icons into `SecureLogin.tsx`, including `EyeOff` for password toggling, and other necessary elements for a streamlined and visually consistent login UI. I've also added standard types and states to the components for form handling. The goal is to make a really clean and readable import.\n\nI'm now implementing the password visibility toggle using the `Eye` and `EyeOff` icons, and I've started on mock email autofill based on the development sandbox selection. I am going to have the default value be empty, as the user selects the role from the developer sandbox panel.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
